{
  "Calorimetry is the measurement of:": "",
  "Pressure changes under normal conditions": "",
  "Electrical current in a circuit wire": "",
  "Heat transfer during chemical or physical processes": "",
  "Volume changes in a sealed container": "",
  "Calorimetry is the science of measuring heat transfer during chemical or physical processes using a calorimeter.": "",
  "A calorimeter works by:": "",
  "Counting molecules in a solution": "",
  "Measuring temperature change of water surrounding a reaction": "",
  "Measuring pressure of gases directly": "",
  "Weighing products of a reaction": "",
  "A calorimeter measures heat by tracking the temperature change of water surrounding the reaction: q = mcDeltaT.": "",
  "In a coffee-cup calorimeter, the assumption is:": "",
  "Temperature stays constant during the test": "",
  "No heat is lost to the surroundings": "",
  "All heat escapes to the environment": "",
  "Only gases are measured in the test": "",
  "A coffee-cup calorimeter assumes no heat is lost to the surroundings (perfect insulation), so all heat from the reaction goes into the water.": "",
  "The heat released by a reaction equals:": "",
  "The volume of the container used": "",
  "The heat absorbed by the water (q = mcDeltaT)": "",
  "Zero always in every reaction": "",
  "The mass of the reactants used": "",
  "By conservation of energy: q_reaction = -q_water. The heat released by the reaction is absorbed by the water.": "",
  "If water temperature rises in a calorimeter, the reaction is:": "",
  "Exothermic (releases heat)": "",
  "Endothermic (absorbs heat)": "",
  "Impossible to determine": "",
  "At chemical equilibrium": "",
  "If the water temperature rises, the reaction released heat into the water, making it exothermic.": "",
  "A bomb calorimeter measures reactions at constant:": "",
  "Temperature": "",
  "Volume": "",
  "Mass": "",
  "Pressure": "",
  "A bomb calorimeter is a sealed, rigid container, so reactions occur at constant volume. Coffee-cup calorimeters measure at constant pressure.": "",
  "If 200 g of water rises by 5 degrees C in a calorimeter, heat absorbed is:": "",
  "200 J": "",
  "4,184 J": "",
  "5,000 J": "",
  "1,000 J": "",
  "q = mcDeltaT = 200 x 4.184 x 5 = 4,184 J.": "",
  "If water temperature decreases in a calorimeter, the reaction is:": "",
  "Endothermic (absorbs heat from the water)": "",
  "Exothermic (releases heat to the water)": "",
  "Neither exothermic nor endothermic": "",
  "At equilibrium with no energy change": "",
  "If water cools down, the reaction absorbed heat from the water, making it endothermic.": "",
  "The law of conservation of energy in calorimetry states:": "",
  "Heat lost by one substance equals heat gained by another": "",
  "Energy is created during exothermic reactions only": "",
  "Energy is destroyed during endothermic reactions": "",
  "Heat always flows from cold objects to hot objects": "",
  "Conservation of energy: q_lost = -q_gained. The heat released by one part of the system is absorbed by another.": "",
  "A coffee-cup calorimeter is an example of a:": "",
  "Constant pressure calorimeter": "",
  "Constant volume calorimeter": "",
  "Constant temperature calorimeter": "",
  "Variable pressure calorimeter": "",
  "A coffee-cup calorimeter is open to the atmosphere, so reactions occur at constant (atmospheric) pressure.": "",
  "What is a calorimeter?": "",
  "A device used to measure the heat exchanged during a chemical or physical process": "",
  "A device used to measure the electrical resistance of a wire or metal sample": "",
  "A device used to measure the volume of gas produced during a chemical reaction": "",
  "A device used to measure the mass of reactants before and after a reaction": "",
  "A calorimeter is an insulated device that measures the heat exchanged during chemical or physical processes by tracking temperature changes.": "",
  "What is the definition of calorimetry?": "",
  "The science of measuring heat changes during chemical and physical processes": "",
  "The science of measuring pressure changes during chemical reactions only": "",
  "The science of measuring the speed at which chemical reactions take place": "",
  "The science of measuring the mass of products formed in chemical reactions": "",
  "Calorimetry is the branch of science concerned with measuring the heat of chemical reactions or physical changes.": "",
  "What is a 'coffee-cup calorimeter'?": "",
  "A simple calorimeter made from insulated cups that measures heat at constant pressure": "",
  "A sealed metal container that measures heat at constant volume under high pressure": "",
  "A device that heats coffee to a specific temperature for laboratory taste testing": "",
  "An electronic thermometer that displays temperature readings on a digital screen": "",
  "A coffee-cup calorimeter is a simple, inexpensive calorimeter made from insulated cups (often Styrofoam). It operates at constant atmospheric pressure.": "",
  "What is a 'bomb calorimeter'?": "",
  "A sealed, rigid device that measures heat at constant volume for combustion reactions": "",
  "An open container that measures heat at constant pressure for all types of reactions": "",
  "A device that creates explosions to measure the force of chemical reactions in labs": "",
  "A thermometer that measures the temperature of bombs before they are detonated": "",
  "A bomb calorimeter is a sturdy, sealed device used to measure the heat of combustion reactions at constant volume. The 'bomb' is the sealed reaction chamber.": "",
  "Define 'heat of reaction' as measured by calorimetry.": "",
  "The total heat absorbed or released during a chemical reaction at specified conditions": "",
  "The temperature at which a chemical reaction begins to occur in a calorimeter device": "",
  "The mass of water needed to absorb all the heat from a reaction in a calorimeter": "",
  "The time required for a reaction to reach completion inside a sealed calorimeter": "",
  "The heat of reaction is the total heat absorbed or released when a reaction takes place, measured by the temperature change of the calorimeter water.": "",
  "What does 'q_reaction = -q_water' mean in calorimetry?": "",
  "The heat released by the reaction equals the heat absorbed by the water and vice versa": "",
  "The reaction and water always have the same temperature at the start of the test": "",
  "The mass of the reaction mixture always equals the mass of the water in the device": "",
  "The volume of the reaction mixture is always negative compared to the water volume": "",
  "q_reaction = -q_water means the heat flows are equal and opposite. If the reaction releases 500 J, the water absorbs 500 J (and vice versa).": "",
  "What is the 'surroundings' in a calorimetry experiment?": "",
  "The water and calorimeter that absorb or release heat from the reaction system": "",
  "The chemicals that are reacting inside the calorimeter during the experiment": "",
  "The laboratory room where the calorimetry experiment is being performed": "",
  "The thermometer that measures the temperature change during the reaction": "",
  "In calorimetry, the surroundings are the water and calorimeter that exchange heat with the reaction (the system).": "",
  "What does 'insulation' mean in the context of a calorimeter?": "",
  "Material that prevents heat from escaping the calorimeter to the outside environment": "",
  "A chemical coating that speeds up the reaction taking place inside the calorimeter": "",
  "An electrical component that powers the thermometer in the calorimeter device": "",
  "The water that surrounds the reaction chamber in the calorimeter setup device": "",
  "Insulation in a calorimeter prevents heat exchange with the external environment. Better insulation means more accurate measurements.": "",
  "What is 'constant pressure calorimetry'?": "",
  "Calorimetry performed in an open container where atmospheric pressure stays constant": "",
  "Calorimetry performed in a sealed bomb where volume stays constant during reaction": "",
  "Calorimetry where the temperature of the water is kept constant throughout the test": "",
  "Calorimetry where the mass of water is adjusted to maintain a constant value": "",
  "Constant pressure calorimetry is done in an open container (like a coffee cup) at atmospheric pressure. The heat measured equals the enthalpy change.": "",
  "What does 'specific heat of water' equal and why is it important in calorimetry?": "",
  "4.184 J/g*C; it is the conversion factor used to calculate heat absorbed by water": "",
  "1.000 J/g*C; it is a simplified value used only in advanced chemistry calculations": "",
  "0.449 J/g*C; it is the value for iron which is used as the standard for comparison": "",
  "100.0 J/g*C; it is an approximation used when exact calculations are not needed": "",
  "Water's specific heat is 4.184 J/g*C. It is essential in calorimetry because water is the standard medium for absorbing and measuring heat changes.": "",
  "A student dissolves ammonium nitrate in water inside a coffee-cup calorimeter and the water temperature drops from 25 degrees C to 20 degrees C. This means the dissolving process is:": "",
  "Endothermic because the water lost heat to the dissolving process": "",
  "Exothermic because the water temperature changed during the test": "",
  "Neutral because ammonium nitrate does not react with pure water": "",
  "Impossible to determine without knowing the mass of the ammonium nitrate": "",
  "The water cooled down, meaning it lost heat to the dissolving process. The dissolving absorbed heat from the water, so it is endothermic.": "",
  "In a calorimetry lab, a student burns a peanut under a can of 100 g of water. The water temperature rises from 22 to 52 degrees C. The energy released by the peanut is approximately:": "",
  "12,552 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 30 = 12,552 J of energy": "",
  "4,184 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 10 = 4,184 J of energy": "",
  "21,764 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 52 = 21,764 J of energy": "",
  "418.4 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 1 = 418.4 J of energy only": "",
  "q = mcDeltaT = 100 x 4.184 x (52-22) = 100 x 4.184 x 30 = 12,552 J.": "",
  "A student mixes 50 mL of HCl with 50 mL of NaOH in a calorimeter. The temperature rises from 22 to 29 degrees C. Assuming the solution has the density and specific heat of water, the heat released is:": "",
  "2,928.8 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 7 = 2,928.8 J released": "",
  "1,464.4 J because q = 50 x 4.184 x 7 = 1,464.4 J released": "",
  "12,133 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 29 = 12,133.6 J released": "",
  "418.4 J because q = 100 x 4.184 x 1 = 418.4 J only released": "",
  "Total mass = 50 + 50 = 100 g. q = 100 x 4.184 x 7 = 2,928.8 J. The temperature rise shows the reaction is exothermic.": "",
  "A scientist uses a bomb calorimeter to measure the energy content of a food sample. The calorimeter contains 2,000 g of water, and the temperature rises by 3.5 degrees C. The heat released by the food is:": "",
  "29,288 J because q = 2,000 x 4.184 x 3.5 = 29,288 J of heat": "",
  "14,644 J because q = 1,000 x 4.184 x 3.5 = 14,644 J of heat": "",
  "8,368 J because q = 2,000 x 4.184 x 1.0 = 8,368 J of heat": "",
  "7,000 J because q = 2,000 x 1.000 x 3.5 = 7,000 J of heat": "",
  "q = mcDeltaT = 2,000 x 4.184 x 3.5 = 29,288 J.": "",
  "A student places a hot 50 g metal sample into 150 g of water at 20 degrees C. The water rises to 25 degrees C. The heat lost by the metal equals:": "",
  "3,138 J because the water gained q = 150 x 4.184 x 5 = 3,138 J": "",
  "1,046 J because the water gained q = 50 x 4.184 x 5 = 1,046 J": "",
  "6,276 J because the metal lost q = 150 x 4.184 x 10 = 6,276 J": "",
  "418.4 J because the water gained q = 100 x 4.184 x 1 = 418.4 J": "",
  "The heat gained by water = heat lost by metal. q_water = 150 x 4.184 x 5 = 3,138 J. So the metal lost 3,138 J.": "",
  "A food company uses a bomb calorimeter to determine the caloric content of a new energy bar. If burning the bar raises 1,500 g of water by 40 degrees C, the bar contains approximately:": "",
  "60 food Calories because q = 1,500 x 4.184 x 40 = 251,040 J = 60 kcal": "",
  "250 food Calories because 251,040 J divided by 1,000 gives 251 Calories": "",
  "6 food Calories because 251,040 J divided by 41,840 gives about 6 total": "",
  "600 food Calories because you multiply kilojoules by 10 for food Calories": "",
  "q = 1,500 x 4.184 x 40 = 251,040 J = 251.04 kJ. Convert: 251,040 / 4,184 = 60,000 cal = 60 kcal = 60 food Calories.": "",
  "A student notices that when calcium chloride dissolves in water, the water gets warm. In the calorimeter, this means:": "",
  "The dissolving is exothermic and released heat into the surrounding water": "",
  "The dissolving is endothermic and absorbed heat from the surrounding water": "",
  "The calorimeter malfunctioned and needs to be recalibrated before further use": "",
  "Calcium chloride decomposed into calcium and chlorine gas during dissolving": "",
  "When dissolving releases heat and the water temperature rises, the process is exothermic (q is negative for the dissolving process).": "",
  "A student's calorimetry results are lower than the accepted value. The most likely source of error is:": "",
  "Heat was lost to the surroundings through imperfect insulation of the device": "",
  "The thermometer was reading temperatures that were too high throughout the test": "",
  "Extra heat was generated from friction between the water and the container walls": "",
  "The water's specific heat was actually higher than 4.184 J/g*C during the test": "",
  "The most common error in calorimetry is heat loss to the surroundings. If some heat escapes, the measured temperature change is smaller, giving a lower calculated q.": "",
  "A nutritionist wants to know the energy content of a cracker. She burns it in a calorimeter with 500 g of water and measures a temperature increase of 8 degrees C. The energy content is:": "",
  "16,736 J or about 4 food Calories from the cracker combustion": "",
  "4,184 J or about 1 food Calorie from the cracker combustion": "",
  "33,472 J or about 8 food Calories from the cracker combustion": "",
  "2,092 J or about 0.5 food Calories from the cracker combustion": "",
  "q = 500 x 4.184 x 8 = 16,736 J. Convert: 16,736 / 4,184 = 4,000 cal = 4 kcal = 4 food Calories.": "",
  "In a chemistry class, students test whether dissolving table salt or dissolving baking soda releases more heat. They use identical calorimeters with 100 g of water. The substance that causes the larger temperature increase:": "",
  "Releases more heat per gram because a larger DeltaT means more heat transferred": "",
  "Absorbs more heat per gram because temperature and heat are inversely related": "",
  "Has a higher specific heat because it changed the water temperature more": "",
  "Must have a larger mass because heavier substances always produce more heat": "",
  "With the same mass of water, a larger temperature increase means more heat was transferred: q = mcDeltaT. The substance causing a bigger DeltaT released more heat.": ""
